Refining mass dilation with shape, structure, and gravity

You’re pointing to the right missing pieces: the “dilation” felt or seen depends not just on total mass, but on how that mass is distributed (shape, density, rigidity), how gravity acts on it (external field strength and gradients), and how large/compact the object is relative to spacetime scales. Below is a coherent framework that binds these together.

---

Core invariants and dilation factors

• Proper time dilation (gravity, Schwarzschild-like):d\tau = dt\,\sqrt{1 - \frac{2G M_{\text{grav}}}{R_{\text{char}} c^2}}
• Label meanings: \(M_{\text{grav}}\) is the gravitational mass including binding energy; \(R_{\text{char}}\) is a characteristic radius that reflects shape/structure (defined below).
• Compactness:\mathcal{C} = \frac{G M_{\text{grav}}}{R_{\text{char}} c^2}
Higher \(\mathcal{C}\) increases gravitational time dilation.

• Velocity-based dilation (unchanged):\gamma = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{v^2}{c^2}}},\quad m_{\text{eff}} = \gamma m_0



---

Gravitational mass vs. baryonic mass (binding energy)

• Gravitational mass with self-energy:M_{\text{grav}} = M_{\text{baryon}} + \frac{E_{\text{bind}}}{c^2}
• Newtonian binding energy (rough estimate for uniform sphere):E_{\text{bind}} \approx -\,\frac{3}{5}\,\frac{G M_{\text{baryon}}^2}{R_{\text{eff}}}

• Refinement for shape: replace \(R_{\text{eff}}\) with \(R_{\text{char}}\) that encodes geometry; non-spherical shapes adjust the prefactor via a form factor \(f_{\text{shape}}\) (see below).

• Implication: As mass increases or is compacted (smaller \(R_{\text{char}}\)), \(|E_{\text{bind}}|\) grows, reducing \(M_{\text{grav}}\) slightly relative to baryonic content; in strong gravity (relativistic stars) this correction is substantial.


---

Shape, structure, and “characteristic radius”

• Characteristic radius with shape factor:R_{\text{char}} = f_{\text{shape}}\,R_{\text{vol}}
• Volume-equivalent radius:R_{\text{vol}} = \left(\frac{3V}{4\pi}\right)^{1/3}

• Shape factor examples:• Sphere: \(f_{\text{shape}} = 1\)
• Oblate/prolate ellipsoid: \(f_{\text{shape}} = \left(\frac{a b c}{R_{\text{vol}}^3}\right)^{\alpha}\), with \(\alpha\) chosen so that gravitational potential averages match observed multipole moments.
• Rod/disc limits: larger deviations yield \(f_{\text{shape}}<1\) (more compact field) or \(>1\) (more spread) depending on directionality of mass.


• Quadrupole contribution (external field footprint):\Phi(\vec{r}) \approx -\frac{G M_{\text{grav}}}{r} - \frac{G}{2 r^3}\,Q_{ij}\,\hat{r}_i \hat{r}_j
• Quadrupole tensor:Q_{ij} = \int \rho(\vec{x})\,(3 x_i x_j - r^2 \delta_{ij})\,d^3x

• Interpretation: Non-spherical mass raises/lowers local gravitational potential and hence the redshift/time-dilation experienced by nearby clocks depending on orientation.



