Material rigidity, tidal response, and effective size

• Tidal deformability (Love number \(k_2\)):k_2 \sim \text{function of EOS, rigidity, and density profile}
• Effect: Softer bodies deform under external gravity, increasing quadrupole terms and changing \(\Phi\), which modifies local dilation.

• Stressed-state energy (structure under load):E_{\text{struct}} = \int \sigma_{ij}\,\epsilon_{ij}\,dV
• Contribution to gravitational mass:M_{\text{grav}} \rightarrow M_{\text{grav}} + \frac{E_{\text{struct}}}{c^2}

• Meaning: Internal stresses (compression, rotation-induced flattening) add energy that slightly shifts gravitational mass and the compactness ratio.

• Rotation (frame-dragging and flattening):• Angular momentum: \(J = I \Omega\), with \(I\) depending on shape.
• **Oblateness increases quadrupole \(J_2\), modifying \(\Phi\) and local redshift; in GR, rotation also introduces frame-dragging that affects clock rates off the symmetry axis.



