A workable “mass dilation” ratio that ties it all together

Define the dilation ratio as the inverse of the local time-dilation factor, but expressed in terms that include mass, shape, and structure:

• Local mass dilation mapping (gravity-based):{
\mathcal{D}_{m}(\vec{x}) \;=\; \left[\,1 - \frac{2G}{c^2}\,\frac{M_{\text{grav}}^{\text{eff}}(\vec{x})}{R_{\text{char}}^{\text{eff}}(\vec{x})}\,\right]^{-1/2}
}

• Effective gravitational mass:M_{\text{grav}}^{\text{eff}} = M_{\text{baryon}} + \frac{E_{\text{bind}} + E_{\text{struct}} + E_{\text{rot}}}{c^2}
• Rotation energy: \(E_{\text{rot}} = \frac{1}{2} I \Omega^2\)

• Effective characteristic radius (orientation-aware):R_{\text{char}}^{\text{eff}}(\vec{x}) = \frac{R_{\text{vol}}}{\displaystyle \left[\,1 + \beta_{\text{quad}}(\vec{x})\,\right]}
• Quadrupole correction:\beta_{\text{quad}}(\vec{x}) = \frac{Q_{ij}\,\hat{n}_i \hat{n}_j}{2\,M_{\text{grav}}\,R_{\text{vol}}^2}
with \(\hat{n}\) the direction from the object to the clock/location \(\vec{x}\).

• Interpretation: Increasing mass, increasing internal energy (stresses/rotation), and increasing compactness (smaller effective radius or shape-induced focusing) all raise \(\mathcal{D}_m\) (your “mass dilation”), mirroring stronger gravitational time dilation.


